<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The starting situation</span>
<h2 class="h2">May 2017: a credible DTC product, an unproven acquisition motion</h2>
<p class="body"><strong>Company:</strong> Factor_ — prepared, ready-to-eat meal delivery DTC brand. Real product credibility; strong early customer base; a category (prepared meals as DTC subscription) that was rapidly proving out across the broader meal-kit landscape.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>The constraint:</strong> Paid acquisition was effectively unbuilt — the company hadn't yet cracked the meta-ads creative + funnel architecture needed to scale customer acquisition at meal-kit-category economics. Lifecycle email marketing existed but was underused; meaningful prospect segments weren't being nurtured to conversion. The growth ceiling was the marketing infrastructure, not the product or the market.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>What Treetop was asked to own:</strong> Chief Marketing Officer role for the engagement. Reporting directly to the CEO. Own all marketing media investment, customer acquisition, lifecycle marketing, and the team that executed it. Build the acquisition engine that would let the company capture the demand the product had already earned.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What we built</span>
<h2 class="h2">The acquisition engine</h2>

<h3 class="h3">Paid social acquisition (Meta)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Scaled spend from $0 to $4K+/day</strong> over the engagement window. A multi-tier funnel structure separating top-of-funnel prospecting, mid-funnel education, and bottom-of-funnel conversion creative — each layer creatively distinct and audience-targeted.</li>
<li><strong>Blended CAC: $129 → $64.</strong> A 50% cut in customer acquisition cost while scaling spend by orders of magnitude — the opposite of what most operators see when they aggressively scale paid. The driver was creative architecture + funnel discipline, not just better targeting.</li>
<li><strong>775+ unique Meta ads tested.</strong> Continuous variant testing — copy hooks, video formats, imagery, gifs, audience permutations. A proprietary campaign setup structure that surfaced winning combinations faster than the standard A/B-test cadence.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Lifecycle email marketing</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1,100% revenue lift from email channels.</strong> Built automated lifecycle messaging flows segmented by prospect stage — first-visit, abandoned cart, post-purchase, re-engagement, win-back, loyalty. Each flow tuned to the audience's stage and intent rather than treated as undifferentiated email blasts.</li>
<li><strong>Team mentorship contributing to a 34% lift in email-channel sales</strong> separately — the engagement also developed the junior team members' lifecycle marketing capability so the gains compounded after the campaign launches.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">The compounding effect</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>66% revenue growth in six months (Jul-Dec 2017).</strong> The combined effect of expanded paid acquisition + improved lifecycle email economics + the scaling team executing both with rising discipline.</li>
<li><strong>INC 5000 recognition in 2017 and 2018.</strong> Two consecutive years on the list of America's fastest-growing private companies.</li>
<li><strong>HelloFresh acquisition.</strong> The trajectory established in this engagement was a meaningful contributor to the company's eventual acquisition by HelloFresh — one of the most-recognized exits in the DTC food category.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

